    readTime: '3 min',
    summary: 'Meat grown from animal cells in laboratories is slowly reaching restaurant menus and supermarket shelves.',
    content: `A new kind of meat is coming to restaurants and supermarkets. [Cultivated] meat — also called lab-grown or cell-based meat — is made by taking cells from an animal and growing them in a [laboratory] until they form real muscle tissue. No animals need to be killed in the process.

The idea sounds like science fiction, but it is becoming [reality]. In Singapore, which became the first country to [approve] cultivated chicken for sale in 2020, customers can now order it in some restaurants. The United States [approved] two cultivated chicken products in 2023. More [approvals] are expected around the world.

The [potential] [environmental] [benefits] are [significant]. [Traditional] meat [production] is one of the biggest [contributors] to [greenhouse] gas [emissions]. It also uses enormous amounts of land and water. [Cultivated] meat could produce up to 90% fewer [emissions] and use far less land.

There are still [challenges], however. At the moment, cultivated meat is [expensive] to produce. A single burger made from [cultivated] beef [currently] costs several times more than a [conventional] one. [Manufacturers] are working to [reduce] costs, but it will take time before [prices] can [compete] with [regular] meat.

[Consumer] [acceptance] is also a question. Many people find the idea of lab-grown meat [unpleasant], even if it is [nutritionally] [identical] to [conventional] meat. Some people worry about whether it is [natural] or [safe]. [Studies] show that [younger] people are more [open] to trying it.

"We are at the beginning of a food [revolution]," said Dr Alex Kim, a food scientist at Imperial College London. "In twenty years, eating an animal that was [slaughtered] might seem as [strange] to us as some other [outdated] [practices] seem today."`,
